[[Category:Pandanus|List of Pandanus species]] [[Category:Lists of plant species|Pandanus]]

{{Swedish National Parks}} National parks of Sweden are managed by the [[Environmental Protection Agency (Sweden)|Swedish Environmental Protection Agency]] (EPA) ({{lang-sv|Naturvårdsverket}}) and owned by the state. The goal of the [[national park]] service is to create a system of protected areas that represent all the distinct natural regions of the country.<ref name="swedishepa"/> In 1909, [[Sweden]] became the first country in Europe to establish such parks when nine were opened following the [[Riksdag]] passing of a law on national parks that year. This was followed by the establishment of seven parks between 1918 and 1962 and thirteen between 1982 and 2009, with the latest being [[Kosterhavet National Park]].<ref name="swedishepa">{{cite web|url=http://www.naturvardsverket.se/en/In-English/Start/Nature-conservation-and-wildlife/Nature-conservation-and-species-protection/National-parks-and-other-ways-to-protect-nature/|title=National parks and other ways to protect nature|publisher=[[Naturvårdsverket]] (Swedish Environmental Protection Agency)|accessdate=2009-06-11|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110307142117/http://naturvardsverket.se/en/In-English/Start/Nature-conservation-and-wildlife/Nature-conservation-and-species-protection/National-parks-and-other-ways-to-protect-nature/|archivedate=2011-03-07|df=}}</ref> There are currently 29 national parks in Sweden, comprising a total area of 731,589 [[hectare]]s (1,807,796 [[acre]]s);<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naturvardsverket.se/sv/Start/Naturvard/Skydd-av-natur/Nationalparker/|title=Nationalparker|language=Swedish|publisher=Naturvårdsverket (Swedish Environmental Protection Agency)|accessdate=2011-06-18|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69NELrGcH?url=http://www.naturvardsverket.se/sv/Start/Naturvard/Skydd-av-natur/Nationalparker/|archivedate=2012-07-23|df=}}</ref> six more are scheduled to open by 2013.<ref name="förslag2"/>
According to the EPA, Swedish national parks must represent unique landscape types and be effectively protected and used for research, recreation, and tourism without damaging nature.<ref name="criteria">{{cite web|url=http://www.naturvardsverket.se/Start/Naturvard/Skydd-av-natur/Nationalparker/Forslag-till-nya-nationalparker/Fakta-om-nationalparker/|title=Fakta om nationalparker|language=Swedish|publisher=Naturvårdsverket (Swedish Environmental Protection Agency)|accessdate=2011-06-18|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130113202619/http://www.naturvardsverket.se/Start/Naturvard/Skydd-av-natur/Nationalparker/Forslag-till-nya-nationalparker/Fakta-om-nationalparker/|archivedate=2013-01-13|df=}}</ref> Mountain terrain dominates approximatively 90% of the parks' combined area. The reason for this is the extensive mountain areas taken up by the large northern parks—[[Sarek National Park]] and [[Padjelanta National Park]] each cover approximately {{convert|200000|ha|acre|abbr=off}}.<ref name="sarek"/><ref name="padjelanta"/> Many of the northern parks are part of the [[Laponian area]], one of Sweden's [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]]s due to its preserved natural landscape and habitat for the native [[reindeer]]-herding [[Sami people]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whc.unesco.org/pg.cfm?cid=31&id_site=774|title=Laponian Area|publisher=[[World Heritage Site|UNESCO World Heritage Centre]]|accessdate=2009-06-11}}</ref> The southernmost parks—[[Söderåsen National Park]], [[Dalby Söderskog National Park]] and [[Stenshuvud National Park]]—are covered with [[Temperate broadleaf and mixed forest|broadleaf forest]] and together cover approximately {{convert|2000|ha|acre|0|sigfig=2|abbr=on}}.<ref name="söderåsen"/><ref name="dalby"/><ref name="stenshuvud"/> Fulufjället National Park is part of [[PAN Parks]],<ref name="Fulufjället"/> a network founded by the [[World Wildlife Fund]] (WWF) to provide better long-term conservation and tourism management of European national parks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panparks.org/Introduction/Vision|archive-url=https://archive.is/20030613113554/http://www.panparks.org/Introduction/Vision|dead-url=yes|archive-date=2003-06-13|title=Vision|publisher=PAN Parks|accessdate=2009-06-25}}</ref>
