The '''Swedish–Russian Arc-of-Meridian expedition''' took place during five summer seasons and one winter season at [[Svalbard]], from 1899. The purpose of the mission was to measure the [[meridian arc]]s, in order to calculate whether earth flattening was larger at the [[Geographical pole|poles]].
The measurements were done by an establishing a chain of triangulation points from [[Keilhaufjellet]] in [[Sørkapp Land]] to [[Vesle Tavleøya]] north of [[Nordaustlandet]]. The Russians were responsible for the southern measurements, while the Swedes performed the northern measurements from a base at [[Crozierpynten]] in the fjord of [[Sorgfjorden]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cruise-handbook.npolar.no/en/hornsund/arc-of-meridian.html |title=Cruise Handbook for Svalbard |chapter=The Arc of Meridian Expedition |first1=Jørn |last1=Henriksen |first2= Kristin |last2=Prestvold |publisher=Norwegian Polar Institute|year=2009 |accessdate=25 July 2013 }}</ref>
